text: A multi-tissue structure is categorized as a type of multicellular anatomical structure and also as a type of entity that necessarily comprises some tissue as part of its composition. It is defined as an anatomical structure that incorporates two or more portions of tissue of at least two different types. Through specific morphogenetic processes, these tissues come together to form a single distinct structural unit, which is demarcated by bona fide boundaries from other distinct structural units of different types. Additionally, "multi-tissue structures" is a term related as a synonym to multi-tissue structure.

Epithelium, which is a type of tissue, is defined as a portion of tissue that consists of one or more layers of epithelial cells connected to each other by cell junctions and is underlain by a basal lamina, with examples including simple squamous epithelium, glandular cuboidal epithelium, transitional epithelium, and myoepithelium. It is also synonymous with epithelial tissue and portion of epithelium. Epithelium encompasses both multilaminar and unilaminar epithelium, indicating its diverse structural composition. Additionally, epithelium is characterized by having at least a part of some basement membrane of epithelium.

Simple cuboidal epithelium is a type of unilaminar epithelium and also a type of cuboidal epithelium. It is defined as unilaminar epithelium that consists of a single layer of cuboidal cells. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "epithelium simplex cuboideum" and a related synonym "simple cuboidal epithelia."

Simple columnar epithelium is a type of unilaminar and columnar epithelium. It is defined as a unilaminar epithelium consisting of a single layer of columnar cells, with examples including ciliated columnar epithelium, gastric epithelium, and microvillus columnar epithelium. It has broad synonyms such as columnar epithelium and columnar epithlium, while its exact synonyms include epithelium simplex columnare and simple columnar epithelium itself. Additionally, it has a related synonym which is simple columnar epithelia.

Multilaminar epithelium is a type of epithelium defined as epithelium which consists of more than one layer of epithelial cells that may or may not be in contact with a basement membrane, with examples including keratinized stratified squamous epithelium and ciliated stratified columnar epithelium. It is exactly synonymous with stratified epithelium and is relatedly synonymous with laminated epithelium.

Atypical epithelium is a type of epithelium defined as epithelium that consists of epithelial cells not arranged in one or more layers. It is exactly synonymous with heterogeneous epithelium and is also relatedly known as atypical epithelia.

A cavitated compound organ is a type of compound organ that also falls under the category of entities that have at least a part constituting some anatomical cavity. It is defined as a compound organ containing one or more macroscopic anatomical spaces. Furthermore, it is synonymous with "cavitated organ" and is relatedly referred to as "cavitated compound organs." This organ is essentially the same as entities found at the intersection of being a compound organ and having at least a part that is an anatomical cavity.

Unilaminar epithelium is a type of epithelium defined as epithelium which consists of a single layer of epithelial cells, with examples including endothelium, mesothelium, and glandular squamous epithelium. It is exactly synonymous with simple epithelium and is also relatedly referred to as unilaminar epithelia.

Chyme is a type of bodily fluid and ingested food with the definition of being a semifluid mass of partly digested food expelled by the stomach into the duodenum. It also has the exact synonym "chymus."

Chyle is a type of caro, organism substance, and something that at least has part some lymph. It is defined as a bodily fluid consisting of a milky fluid that includes lymph and emulsified fats, formed in the small intestine during the digestion of ingested fats.

Mucus is a type of bodily fluid and a secretion of the exocrine gland. It is defined as a bodily fluid consisting of a slippery secretion of the lining of the mucous membranes in the body. Mucus is a viscous colloid that contains antiseptic enzymes, such as lysozyme, and immunoglobulins. It is produced by goblet cells in the mucous membranes that cover the surfaces of these membranes, comprising mucins and inorganic salts suspended in water.

Interstitial fluid is a type of organism substance and also a type of substance that is at least part of some tissue. It is defined as a bodily fluid consisting of a solution which bathes and surrounds the cells of multicellular animals, being the main component of the extracellular fluid, which also includes plasma and transcellular fluid. Moreover, interstitial fluid has exact synonyms, including intercellular fluid and tissue fluid.

The thoracic segment of the trunk is a type of subdivision of both the trunk and the organism along the main body axis, and it is characterized as something that includes at least a part of the thoracic skeleton. It is defined as the subdivision of the trunk that lies between the head and the abdomen. Additionally, the thoracic segment of the trunk is exactly synonymous with the term "thorax" and is relatedly referred to as the anterior subdivision of the trunk, upper body, and upper trunk.

An embryo is a type of multicellular organism and an anatomical entity that encompasses the organism in its early stages of growth and differentiation. These stages are marked by cleavage, the formation of fundamental tissues, and the development of primitive organs and organ systems. Specifically, for mammals, this developmental process starts with zygote formation and concludes with birth. For insects, it begins at zygote formation and ends with larval hatching. In the case of plant zygotic embryos, the process ranges from zygote formation to the end of seed dormancy. For plant vegetative embryos, it extends from the initial determination of the cell or group of cells to form an embryo until the point when the embryo becomes independent of the parent plant. Additionally, the term "embryo" is exactly synonymous with "embryonic organism" and is relatedly synonymous with both "developing organism" and "developmental tissue."

A germ layer, defined as a layer of cells produced during the process of gastrulation during the early development of the animal embryo, distinct from other such layers of cells, marks an early step of cell differentiation. Specifically, the three types of germ layers are the endoderm, ectoderm, and mesoderm. It also has a broad synonym known as embryonic tissue and an exact synonym, germinal layer. Additionally, primary germ layer is considered a narrow synonym, while related synonyms include embryonic germ layer and embryonic germ layers. Furthermore, neural crest is a type of germ layer.

Ectoderm is a type of germ layer and has the definition of being the primary germ layer that is the outermost of the embryo's three germ layers, which gives rise to the epidermis and neural tissue. It is also a type of entity that at least develops from or immediately transforms some presumptive ectoderm. Additionally, ectoderm has an exact synonym, which is embryonic ectoderm.

Endoderm is a type of germ layer that develops from and immediately transforms presumptive endoderm. It is defined as the primary germ layer that lies remote from the surface of the embryo and gives rise to internal tissues such as the gut. Additionally, endoderm is related to and synonymous with entoderm.

Mesoderm is a type of germ layer that develops from and immediately transforms some presumptive mesoderm. It is defined as the middle germ layer of the embryo, situated between the endoderm and ectoderm. Additionally, mesoderm is related to and synonymously referred to as embryonic mesoderm, entire mesoderm, and mesodermal mantle.

Stomodeum is a subdivision of a tube and partakes in several relationships; it is part of the ectoderm and is also part of the future mouth. It is defined as the anterior part of the embryonic digestive tract that develops into a mouth, including an invagination of the ectoderm and the stomodeal cavity. Furthermore, stomodeum has a broad synonym, stomodeal-hypophyseal primordium, and exact synonyms including mouth primordium, primitive oral cavity, stomatodeum, and stomodaeum. Related synonyms for stomodeum encompass mouth pit, oral ectoderm, and oral pit.

The heart is the same as something that intersects something that is a primary circulatory organ and something that at least has a part of some cardiac chamber. It is a type of caro 0000000, mesoderm-derived structure, thoracic segment organ, primary circulatory organ, structure with developmental contribution from neural crest, something that at least part of some heart plus pericardium, something that at least has part some cardiac chamber, and something that at least develops from some heart tube. The heart is defined as a myogenic muscular circulatory organ found in the vertebrate cardiovascular system composed of chambers of cardiac muscle, and it is the primary circulatory organ. Furthermore, the heart has exact synonyms including chambered heart and vertebrate heart, a narrow synonym of branchial heart, and a related synonym of cardium.

The brain is an organ that is derived from the ectoderm and is part of the central nervous system. It develops from, and is an immediate transformation of, the future brain. The brain, also known as the encephalon, suprasegmental levels of the nervous system, suprasegmental structures, synganglion, or simply the brain, is defined as the center of the nervous system in all vertebrate and most invertebrate animals. However, some primitive animals such as jellyfish and starfish have a decentralized nervous system without a brain, and sponges lack any nervous system at all. In vertebrates, the brain is located in the head, protected by the skull, and is close to the primary sensory apparatus of vision, hearing, balance, taste, and smell.

The lens of the camera-type eye is a multifaceted structure that plays a critical role in vision. It is derived from the ectoderm and is an integral part of the anterior segment of the eyeball, which develops from the lens vesicle. This lens is not only transparent, allowing it to refract light to be focused on the retina but is also identified by several synonyms. It is exactly known as the camera-type eye lens, eye lens, lens, and lens crystallina. Furthermore, it is relatedly referred to as the crystalline lens, lenses, and the ocular lens.

The retina is a structure derived from the ectoderm and functions as a photoreceptor array. It is part of the posterior segment of the eyeball and the chorioretinal region, developing from the optic cup. The retina is defined as the innermost layer or coating at the back of the eyeball, sensitive to light, where the optic nerve terminates. It is exactly synonymous with the inner layer of the eyeball, retina of camera-type eye, and tunica interna of eyeball. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as Netzhaut and retinas.

The eye is a type of sense organ and is a part of some visual system, serving the role of detecting light. Additionally, it is defined as an organ that detects light and is synonymously related to terms like "light-detecting organ" and "visual apparatus."

A skeletal joint is the same as a union of a synovial joint and a nonsynial joint, and it is a type of articulation as well as a type that connects some skeletal elements. However, a skeletal joint is disjoint with a bone element. The skeletal joint is defined as an anatomical cluster that consists of two or more adjacent skeletal structures, which may be interconnected by various types of tissue according to VSAO. Furthermore, "articulation" and "joint" are considered broad synonyms for a skeletal joint, while "articular joint" and "joints" are related synonyms.

@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:reproductive_system rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onProperty :has_part ;
            owl:someValuesFrom :gonad ],
        :anatomical_system,
        :caro_0000000 ;
    owl:disjointWith :circulatory_system,
        :digestive_system,
        :entire_sense_organ_system,
        :excretory_system,
        :hematopoietic_system,
        :immune_system,
        :integumental_system,
        :musculoskeletal_system,
        :nervous_system,
        :respiratory_system,
        :skeletal_system ;
    :has_definition "Anatomical system that has as its parts the organs concerned with reproduction." ;
    :has_narrow_synonym "genital system",
        "genitalia" ;
    :has_related_synonym "Geschlechtsorgan",
        "animal reproductive system",
        "genital tract",
        "organa genitalia",
        "reproductive tissue",
        "reproductive tract",
        "systemata genitalia" .
text: The reproductive system is a type of anatomical system and can also be considered a type of caro 0000000, which is something that at least has a part of some gonad. It is defined as an anatomical system that has as its parts the organs concerned with reproduction. This system is distinct and separate from several other body systems, including the respiratory, digestive, circulatory, nervous, skeletal, musculoskeletal, hematopoietic, immune, integumental, entire sense organ, and excretory systems. In terms of terminology, the reproductive system has narrow synonyms such as genital system and genitalia, and it is relatedly referred to as Geschlechtsorgan, animal reproductive system, genital tract, organa genitalia, reproductive tissue, reproductive tract, and systemata genitalia.

A gonad is a type of reproductive organ that at least develops from some gonad primordium. It is defined as a reproductive organ that produces and releases eggs (ovary) or sperm (testis). Additionally, gonad has an exact synonym, "gonada," and a related synonym, "gonads."

The skin epidermis is the same as an entity that intersects with both something that is an outer epithelium and something that is at least part of some skin of a body. It is a type of outer epithelium, a type of external integument structure, and also a type of entity that is at least part of some skin of a body. The skin epidermis is defined as the outer epithelial layer of the skin that is superficial to the dermis. Furthermore, it has broad synonyms which include epidermis and skin, and an exact synonym as vertebrate epidermis.

The respiratory system is a type of anatomical system that is distinct and separate from several other systems, including the digestive system, circulatory system, nervous system, skeletal system, musculoskeletal system, hematopoietic system, immune system, integumental system, the entire sense organ system, and the excretory system. It is defined as a functional system consisting of structures involved in respiration. This system is also known by exact synonyms such as "apparatus respiratorius" and "respiratory system," along with related synonyms like "Atmungssystem" and "systema respiratorium."

@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:digestive_system rdfs:subClassOf :anatomical_system ;
    owl:disjointWith :circulatory_system,
        :entire_sense_organ_system,
        :excretory_system,
        :hematopoietic_system,
        :immune_system,
        :integumental_system,
        :musculoskeletal_system,
        :nervous_system,
        :skeletal_system ;
    :has_definition "Anatomical system that has as its parts the organs devoted to the ingestion, digestion, and assimilation of food and the discharge of residual wastes." ;
    :has_related_synonym "alimentary system",
        "alimentary tract",
        "gastrointestinal system",
        "gut" .
text: The digestive system is a type of anatomical system that is distinct and operates separately from several other systems, including the circulatory, nervous, skeletal, musculoskeletal, hematopoietic, immune, integumental, entire sense organ, and excretory systems. It is defined as the anatomical system that encompasses organs devoted to the ingestion, digestion, and assimilation of food, as well as the discharge of residual wastes. Additionally, the digestive system is also referred to by related synonyms such as the alimentary system, alimentary tract, gastrointestinal system, and gut.

The renal system, which is a type of excretory system, is an anatomical system that maintains fluid balance and contributes to electrolyte balance, acid/base balance, and disposal of nitrogenous waste products. It is broadly synonymous with the excretory system and has several exact synonyms, including systema urinaria, systema urinarium, urinary system, and urinary tract. Additionally, the renal system is relatedly referred to as the renal or urinary system and the renal/urinary system.

The circulatory system is a type of anatomical system, which has the definition of being an organ system that passes nutrients (such as amino acids and electrolytes), gases, hormones, blood cells, etc., to and from cells in the body to help fight diseases and help stabilize body temperature and pH to maintain homeostasis. It is also related to the synonym systema cardiovasculare. The circulatory system is disjoint with several other systems, including the nervous system, skeletal system, musculoskeletal system, hematopoietic system, immune system, integumental system, entire sense organ system, and the excretory system.

Adipose tissue is a type of dense irregular connective tissue and is disjoint with neural tissue. It is defined as a portion of connective tissue composed of adipocytes enmeshed in areolar tissue. Adipose tissue has several synonyms; it is exactly known as fat, fat tissue, and fatty tissue. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as adipose, bodyfat, and fatty depot.

Musculature is a type of organ system subdivision, caro, something that at least part of some musculature of the body, and something that at least has part some muscle organ. It is defined as a subdivision of the muscular system corresponding to a subdivision of an organism. Musculature is exactly synonymous with muscle group, muscles set, musculature, musculi, set of muscles, and set of skeletal muscles. Additionally, it is relatedly synonymous with muscle system, muscles, and musculature system.

The nervous system is an anatomical system that develops from and immediately transforms a future nervous system, indicating its dynamic nature in development and function. It is distinctly separate from several other systems including the skeletal system, musculoskeletal system, hematopoietic system, immune system, integumental system, the entire sense organ system, and the excretory system, highlighting its unique role and structure within an organism. The nervous system, also known as the neurological system, has a specific definition: it is an organ system containing predominantly neuron and glial cells. In bilaterally symmetrical organisms, it is arranged in a network of tree-like structures connected to a central body, primarily responsible for regulating and controlling body functions, receiving sensory input, processing this information, and generating behavior. Additionally, it is closely associated with the nerve net and is related to the term systema nervosum, showcasing the variety of terms and concepts connected to this vital system.

The central nervous system (CNS) originates from the ectoderm and is classified as an organ system subdivision. It represents a portion of the nervous system and is something that develops from, and is an immediate transformation of, the future central nervous system. The definition of the central nervous system highlights its role as the core nervous system that integrates and coordinates functions. In vertebrates, it comprises neural tube derivatives, including the brain and spinal cord, while in invertebrates, it consists of central ganglia and a nerve cord. The CNS is also known by its exact synonyms, "CNS" and "systema nervosum centrale," and has a narrow synonym, "cerebrospinal axis," along with a related synonym, "neuraxis."

A nerve is identified as a type of neuron projection bundle, and it forms at least part of the peripheral nervous system. It is defined as an enclosed, cable-like bundle of axons in the peripheral nervous system, originating in a nerve root in the central nervous system (or a condensed nervous structure) and connects with peripheral structures. In terms of terminology, "nerve" has exact synonyms including "nerves" and "peripheral nerve," and it is also relatedly synonymized with "neural subtree."

The sensory system is a type of non-connected functional system, which is also a part of or entirely a sense organ system. It is defined as an anatomical system that overlaps the nervous system and is responsible for receiving and processing sensory information. This system is precisely synonymous with terms including organa sensuum, sense organ subsystem, sense organs, sense organs set, sensory subsystem, and sensory systems. Additionally, it is relatedly synonymous with organa sensuum, sensory organ system, and set of sense organs.
The foregut is a type of subdivision of the digestive tract, defined as the anterior subdivision of a digestive tract. It is also related to the synonyms praeenteron and proenteron.

Hindgut is a type of subdivision of the digestive tract and is defined as the caudalmost subdivision of a digestive tract. It is also something that develops, at least in part, from some mesenchyme. Additionally, hindgut is related to the synonym metenteron.

Primordium is a type of developing anatomical structure and is part of at least some multicellular organisms. It is defined as populations of contiguous cells that are morphologically distinct and already correspond in extent to a later organ or tissue, according to Hartenstein, V. (2004) in FBbt. Additionally, primordium has several related synonyms, including bud, future organ, placode, primordia, and rudiment.

The neural tube is a type of epithelial tube, embryonic tissue, ecto epithelium, and future central nervous system. It is something that at least develops from some neural rod. In the developing vertebrate, the neural tube serves as the embryo's precursor to the central nervous system, which includes the brain and spinal cord. The development process involves the neural groove gradually deepening as the neural folds become elevated, eventually meeting and coalescing in the middle line to convert the groove into a closed tube. This closed tube, known as the neural tube or neural canal (which is strictly speaking the center of the neural tube), has an ectodermal wall that forms the rudiment of the nervous system. Additionally, the neural tube is related to synonyms such as neural primordium, presumptive central nervous system, and tubus neuralis.

An anatomical entity is classified as a type of independent continuant, defined as a biological entity that either represents an individual member of a biological species or embodies the structural organization of an individual member of a biological species.

The skin of the head is synonymous with several terms including adult head zone of skin, head skin, head zone of skin, zone of skin of adult head, and zone of skin of head. It is defined as a zone of skin that is part of a head, which is automatically generated. Furthermore, the skin of the head is the same as something that intersects something in the zone of skin and something that is at least part of some head. It is categorized as a type of head or neck skin, as well as a type of something that is at least part of some head.

The skin of the trunk is equivalent to the intersection of a zone of skin and something that is at least partly part of a trunk. It is defined as a zone of skin that is part of a trunk. Furthermore, the skin of the trunk is classified both as a type of zone of skin and as a type of something that is at least partially part of a trunk. It is exactly synonymous with several terms, including torso zone of skin, trunk skin, trunk zone of skin, zone of skin of torso, and zone of skin of trunk.
Pleural fluid, defined as a transudate contained in the pleural cavity, is a type of secretion of the serous membrane.
Urine is a type of excreta, defined as excretion that is the output of a kidney.
Sweat is a type of secretion of an exocrine gland and is also a type of bodily fluid. It is defined as a secretion produced by a sweat gland and is related to the synonym "skin exudate."

Synovial fluid is a type of transudate and a secretion of serous glands. It is defined as a transudate of plasma that is actively secreted by synovial cells. Additionally, synovial fluid is exactly synonymous with joint fluid.

Smooth muscle tissue is a type of muscle tissue characterized by its unstriated composition, primarily made up of smooth muscle fibers surrounded by a reticulum of collagen and elastic fibers. It distinguishes itself from striated muscle by having a much higher actin/myosin ratio, the absence of conspicuous sarcomeres, and the ability to contract to a much smaller fraction of its resting length. This type of muscle tissue is also known by several exact synonyms, including involuntary muscle, non-striated muscle, smooth muscle, and textus muscularis nonstriatus. Additionally, it has narrow synonyms such as visceral muscle and visceral muscle tissue. Related synonyms include textus muscularis levis and textus muscularis nonstriatus.

Intestinal mucosa is identified as something that intersects mucosa and something that is at least part of some intestine. It is categorized as a type of gastrointestinal system mucosa and also as a type related to something that is at least part of the wall of an intestine. The definition of intestinal mucosa is the mucosal layer that lines the intestine. It has numerous exact synonyms, including bowel mucosa, bowel mucosa of organ, bowel mucous membrane, bowel organ mucosa, intestine mucosa, intestine mucosa of organ, intestine mucous membrane, intestine organ mucosa, mucosa of bowel, mucosa of intestine, mucosa of organ of bowel, mucosa of organ of intestine, mucous membrane of bowel, mucous membrane of intestine, organ mucosa of bowel, organ mucosa of intestine, and tunica mucosa intestini.

The wall of the intestine is the same as an anatomical wall that intersects with something that is at least part of some intestine. It is a type of gut wall and also a type of structure that is at least part of some intestine. The wall of the intestine is defined as an anatomical wall that is part of an intestine. Furthermore, the wall of the intestine has several exact synonyms, including anatomical wall of bowel, anatomical wall of intestine, bowel anatomical wall, bowel wall, intestinal wall, intestine anatomical wall, intestine wall, and wall of bowel. Additionally, it has a related synonym: bowel wall.

The intestinal epithelium, which is the same as the intersection of epithelium and at least part of some intestine, is a type of simple columnar epithelium and also falls under the categories of epithelium of mucosa, digestive tract epithelium, gastrointestinal system epithelium, and something that is at least part of some intestinal mucosa. It is defined as the epithelial layer that lines the intestine. This term has various exact synonyms, including bowel epithelial tissue, bowel epithelium, epithelial tissue of bowel, epithelial tissue of intestine, epithelium of bowel, epithelium of intestine, and intestine epithelial tissue. Additionally, it has a narrow synonym, villous epithelium, and a related synonym, intestine epithelium.

The anal region is a type of organism subdivision, defined as encompassing the anus and surrounding regions, which includes both internal and external areas where present. Additionally, it is related to the synonyms "posterior" and "posterior end of organism."

Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is a type of transudate and is something that at least develops from the choroid plexus of the lateral ventricle. It is defined as a clear, colorless, bodily fluid that occupies the subarachnoid space and the ventricular system around and inside the brain and spinal cord. CSF is also known by its exact synonyms, which include "CSF" and "cerebral spinal fluid." Additionally, it has related synonyms such as "liquor cerebrospinalis" and "spinal fluid."

The skin of the thorax is equivalent to a zone of skin that intersects with at least part of some thoracic segment of the trunk. It is categorized as a type of skin of the trunk and also as a type of entity that is at least part of some thoracic segment of the trunk. The skin of the thorax is defined as a zone of skin that is part of a thorax, which is an automatically generated definition. Furthermore, the skin of the thorax is precisely referred to by several synonyms including thoracic skin, thorax skin, thorax zone of skin, and zone of skin of thorax. Additionally, it is relatedly synonymized as upper body skin.

The pectoral girdle region is defined as an organism subdivision that encompasses the pectoral girdle skeleton along with associated soft tissue, including both skeletal elements and associated tissues like integument and muscle. This region is noted for having only two instances in an organism, namely the right and left pectoral girdle regions. It is identified as the same as the intersection of the appendage girdle region and something that is at least part of some pectoral complex. The pectoral girdle region is categorized as a type of appendage girdle region, lateral structure, and something that is at least part of some pectoral complex, as well as a type of entity that at least has part of some pectoral girdle skeleton. However, it is important to note that the pectoral girdle region is disjointed from the pectoral girdle skeleton itself.

The pectoral girdle region is also known by several synonyms. It has exact synonyms, including "cingulum membri superioris" and "girdle - pectoral." Additionally, it has narrow synonyms such as "cingulum membri superioris," "shoulder girdle," and "upper limb girdle." Moreover, it has related synonyms like "pectoral girdle" and "pectoral region," further illustrating the variety of terms used to describe or relate to this specific region of an organism.

A facial lymphatic vessel is defined as a lymphatic vessel that is part of a face, which is automatically generated. This type of lymphatic vessel is identical to the intersection of a lymphatic vessel and something that is at least part of some face. Furthermore, a facial lymphatic vessel is categorized as a type of lymphatic vessel, a type of entity that is at least part of some face, and also a type of entity that is at least part of some cranial lymph vasculature. It is exactly synonymous with a buccal lymphatic vessel, face lymph vessel, face lymphatic vessel, lymph vessel of face, and lymphatic vessel of face. Additionally, it has a related synonym, FL.

The pectoral lymphatic vessel is identical to the intersection of a lymphatic vessel and something that is at least part of the pectoral girdle region. It is a type of lymphatic vessel and also a type of entity that is at least part of some pectoral girdle region. Additionally, the pectoral lymphatic vessel is related by synonym to PL.

The skeletal system is the same as something that intersects with something that is a subdivision of an organ system and something that at least has a part of some skeleton and something that at least has a part of some articular system. It is a type of subdivision of an organ system, and it is also a type of something that is at least part of some musculoskeletal system, has at least a part of some skeleton, and has at least a part of some articular system. However, the skeletal system is disjoint with several systems, including the bone element, musculoskeletal system, hematopoietic system, immune system, integumental system, entire sense organ system, and excretory system. It is defined as an anatomical system that is a multi-element, multi-tissue anatomical cluster consisting of the skeleton and the articular system. It has an exact synonym, the skeleton system, a narrow synonym, which is a set of all bones and joints, and a related synonym, Skelettsystem.

A subdivision of head is a type of organism subdivision and is also considered a type of something that constitutes at least part of some head. It has an exact synonym, "head subdivision," and related synonyms including "head region" and "region of head."

Face is classified as a type of caro 0000000, and it is also recognized as a type of subdivision of the head. Additionally, the face is defined as a type that requires at least a part of the mouth. The definition of face is detailed as a subdivision of the head that includes parts located deep to the surface of the anterior surface, encompassing the mouth, eyes, and nose (when present). In vertebrates, this definition extends to the facial skeleton and structures that are superficial to the facial skeleton, such as cheeks, mouth, eyeballs, and the skin of the face. Moreover, face is associated with the synonyms facia/facies and visage.

A lymphatic vessel, synonymous with a lymph vessel and also relatedly known as vas lymphaticum, is defined as a vessel that contains or conveys lymph. It originates as an interfibrillar or intercellular cleft or space in a tissue or organ. If the lymphatic vessel is small, it has no distinct walls or walls composed only of endothelial cells, and if large, it resembles a vein in structure. Lymphatic vessels are identified as the same as entities at the intersection of vessels and entities that are at least part of some lymph vasculature. Moreover, a lymphatic vessel is categorized under several types: it is a type of caro 0000000, a general type of vessel, and a type of entity that is at least part of some lymph vasculature or at least has some part of lymph. However, lymphatic vessels are distinctly separate from blood vessels, indicating they do not intersect or share commonality in function or structure with blood vessels.

A bone element is a type of skeletal element and is also a type of entity that has, at least in part, some bone tissue. It is defined as a skeletal element that is composed of bone tissue. Bone element is disjoint with both muscle organ and muscle structure, indicating no overlap between them. In terms of terminology, "bone organ" is an exact synonym for bone element, while "bone" and "bones" are related synonyms.

The digestive tract is defined as a tube that extends from the mouth to the anus, and it is a type of tube. It forms an essential part of the digestive system, connecting the mouth and developing from, as well as undergoing an immediate transformation of, the presumptive gut. It is broadly synonymous with the term "gut" and has exact synonyms that include "digestive tube" and "enteric tract." Additionally, it has narrow synonyms: "alimentary canal" and "alimentary tract," along with related synonyms "digestive canal" and "gut tube."

The ciliary muscle is a type of smooth muscle found in the eye, specifically a part of the intraocular muscles, and is a structure that receives developmental contributions from the neural crest. It is at least partly a component of the ciliary body. The ciliary muscle is defined as a ring of smooth muscle in the middle layer of the eye that controls the eye's accommodation for viewing objects at varying distances and regulates the flow of aqueous humor through Schlemm's canal. This muscle is also known by its exact synonym, musculus ciliarus, and has related synonyms including Bowman's muscles, ciliaris, and musculus ciliaris.

The muscle of the iris is the same as something that is an intersection of a muscle organ and something that is at least part of some iris. It is a type of intraocular muscle and also a type of something that is at least part of some iris. Moreover, the muscle of the iris has exact synonyms including iris muscle, iris muscle organ, and muscle organ of iris.

A muscle organ is a type of organ, muscle structure, caro 0000000, and something that is at least part of some musculature or has some muscle tissue as part of it. It is defined as an organ consisting of a tissue made up of various elongated cells that are specialized to contract and thus to produce movement and mechanical work. Additionally, muscle organ has a broad synonym: muscle.

The jaw skeleton is a type of structure derived from the neural crest and is a subdivision of the skeleton. It is part of both the facial skeleton and the jaw region to some extent. The jaw skeleton is defined as a subdivision of the skeleton that includes both the upper and lower jaw skeletons. It has several synonyms indicating its identity and related structures. Specifically, it is exactly synonymous with "jaw," "jaw cartilage," and "mandibular arch skeleton." Additionally, it has related synonyms that include "anterior splanchnocranium," "jaws," "mandibular arch," "oral jaw skeleton," "pharyngeal arch 1 skeleton," and "visceral arch 1," further elaborating on its connections and relevance within anatomical and physiological contexts.

The lower jaw region is characterized by a variety of classifications and relationships. It is identified as a type of caro 0000000, an organism subdivision, and a structure with developmental contributions from the neural crest. Additionally, it is recognized as a part of the jaw region, having parts of the skeleton of the lower jaw, and developing from the mandibular prominence. The definition provided for the lower jaw region is a "Subdivision of head that consists of the lower jaw skeletal elements plus associated soft tissue (skin, lips, muscle)[cjm]." In terms of nomenclature, the lower jaw region is exactly synonymous with the mandibular part of the mouth and is relatedly referred to as the lower part of the mouth and the mandibular series.

The anterior chamber of the eyeball is a type of chamber of the eyeball and is also considered a part of the anterior segment of the eyeball. It is defined as the space in the eye that is filled with aqueous humor and is bounded anteriorly by the cornea and a small portion of the sclera, and posteriorly by a small portion of the ciliary body, the iris, and part of the crystalline lens. This anatomical structure is known by several exact synonyms, including anterior chamber, anterior chamber of eye, camera anterior, and eye anterior chamber. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as camera anterior bulbi, camera anterior bulbi oculi, and camera oculi anterior.

Uvea is a type of caro, ectoderm-derived structure, organ component layer, and structure with developmental contribution from neural crest. It is also described as part of some anterior segment of the eyeball and has parts including the iris, ciliary body, and optic choroid. The uvea is defined as the pigmented middle of the three concentric layers that make up an eye, consisting of the iris, ciliary body, and choroid. It has exact synonyms such as tunica vasculosa of the eyeball, uveal tract, and is also referred to simply as uvea. Additionally, it has related synonyms including pars iridica retinae, tunica vasculatis oculi, tunica vasculosa bulbi, and vascular layer of the eyeball.

Iris is a type of multi-tissue structure and is also derived from the ectoderm. It is part of the anterior uvea and develops from the optic vesicle. The iris is defined as the adjustable membrane, composed of the stroma and pigmented epithelium, situated just in front of the crystalline lens within the eye. Additionally, iris has related synonyms such as anterior uvea, irides, and irises.

The ciliary body is a multi-tissue structure, derived from the ectoderm, and develops from the neurectoderm. It is a part of the anterior uvea and comprises ciliary muscle and ciliary processes. The ciliary body is defined as the thickened portion of the vascular tunic, situated between the choroid and the iris, and is composed of ciliary muscle and ciliary processes. It is exactly synonymous with the ocular ciliary body and relatedly synonymous with the anterior uvea, ciliary bodies, and corpus ciliare.

The optic choroid is a type of vasculature of the eye and is also considered a part of the uvea and the chorioretinal region. However, it is distinct from the anterior uvea. The optic choroid, defined as the vascular layer containing connective tissue of the eye lying between the retina and the sclera, provides oxygen and nourishment to the outer layers of the retina. It forms the uveal tract along with the ciliary body and iris. The optic choroid is also known by several exact synonyms, including choroid, choroid coat, choroidea, eye choroid, and posterior uvea. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as chorioid and choroidea.

Ciliary epithelium is defined as a double layer covering the ciliary body that produces aqueous humor. It is the same as something that is an intersection of epithelium and something that is at least part of some ciliary body. This epithelium is a type of atypical epithelium, eye epithelium, and it is also a part of the ciliary body. Moreover, ciliary epithelium has exact synonyms including ciliary body epithelium, epithelium of ciliary body, and ocular ciliary epithelium.

The aqueous humor of the eyeball serves multiple roles; it is a type of ocular refractive media, a kind of bodily fluid, and part of the anterior chamber of the eyeball. It is defined as a thick watery refractive medium that fills the space between the lens and the cornea. Additionally, the aqueous humor of the eyeball is precisely known by other names, including aqueous humor, aqueous humour, and humor aquosus.

Vitreous humor is identified as a type of ocular refractive media and also as a part of some vitreous body. It is defined as a transparent, semigelatinous substance that fills the cavity behind the crystalline lens of the eye and in front of the retina. Regarding terminology, vitreous humor is broadly synonymous with "portion of vitreous humor" and has exact synonyms including "humor vitreous," "humor vitreus," "vitreous," and "whole portion of vitreous humor." Additionally, it has related synonyms such as "humoral fluid," "ocular fluid," "vitreous fluid," and "vitreous humour."

The vitreous body is a gelatinous mucoid tissue comprising vitreous humor that fills the cavity behind the crystalline lens of the eye and in front of the retina, according to a modified MP definition. It is classified as a type of head connective tissue, loose connective tissue, and a structure derived from the ectoderm. Furthermore, the vitreous body is part of the vitreous chamber of the eyeball and contains vitreous humor.

The vitreous chamber of the eyeball is a specific type of chamber within the eyeball, which also forms a part of the posterior segment of the eyeball. It is defined as the chamber in the eyeball that encloses the vitreous humor; this chamber is bounded anteriorly by the lens and the ciliary body and posteriorly by the posterior wall of the eyeball. This definition is modified from the original BTO source. Additionally, the vitreous chamber of the eyeball is known by several exact synonyms including camera postrema, camera postrema bulbi oculi, camera vitrea, camera vitrea bulbi, postremal chamber, postremal chamber of eyeball, and vitreous chamber.

The anterior segment of the eyeball is a type of organ subunit, which is also derived from the ectoderm and is part of the eyeball of a camera-type eye. It is distinct and separate from the posterior segment of the eyeball. The anterior segment of the eyeball is defined as any of the parts of the eye that lie in front of, or ventral to, the lens (inclusive). It is also known by several exact synonyms, including anterior eye segment, anterior segment eye, anterior segment of eye, anterior segment of the eye, eye anterior segment, and segmentum anterius (bulbus oculi). Additionally, it has a related synonym: segmentum anterius bulbi oculi.

The posterior segment of the eyeball is classified as an organ subunit, and it derives from the ectoderm. It is also recognized as part of the eyeball within camera-type eyes. The posterior segment is defined as any part of the eye located behind, or dorsal to, the lens, excluding the lens itself. This segment is known by various exact synonyms, including eye posterior segment, posterior eye segment, posterior segment eye, posterior segment of eye, posterior segment of the eye, and segmentum posterius (bulbus oculi). Additionally, it has a related synonym: segmentum posterius bulbi oculi.

The epithelium of the lens has a specific definition, being identified as a layer of epithelial cells that is part of the eye. It is equivalent to something that intersects with something that is epithelium and something that is at least part of some lens of a camera-type eye. This epithelium is categorized as a type of simple cuboidal epithelium and also falls under the category of eye epithelium. Furthermore, it is recognized as a type of something that is at least part of some lens of a camera-type eye. The epithelium of the lens is also known by several exact synonyms, including epithelial tissue of eye lens, epithelial tissue of lens, epithelium lentis, epithelium of eye lens, eye lens epithelial tissue, eye lens epithelium, lens epithelial tissue, and lens epithelium.

Saliva is a type of secretion produced by the exocrine gland, which is defined as a fluid produced in the oral cavity by salivary glands. This fluid is typically used in predigestion, among other functions. Additionally, saliva is exactly synonymous with salivary gland secretion and has related synonyms including saliva normalis, saliva atomaris, and saliva molecularis.

Sebum is a type of secretion of the exocrine gland and is defined as a fatty lubricant matter secreted by sebaceous glands. It is composed of triglyceride oils, wax, squalene, and metabolites of fat-producing cells.

The choroid plexus is a type of brain ventricle choroid plexus, vascular plexus, and part of the vasculature of organs, including the central nervous system. It is also part of some brain ventricles and the tela choroidea. The choroid plexus is defined as a network formed by blood vessels and the tela choroidea, which secretes cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) into the ventricular spaces. It is broadly synonymous with CP and exactly synonymous with chorioid plexus and plexus choroideus. Additionally, related synonyms for the choroid plexus include choroid plexus of cerebral hemisphere, plexus choroideus, and ventricular choroid plexus.

The forebrain is a regional part of the brain that develops from the anterior neural tube and is an immediate transformation of the future forebrain. It is defined as the most anterior region of the brain, including both the telencephalon and diencephalon. The forebrain has a broad synonym, FB, and is also related to the synonym prosencephalon.

Telencephalon is a type of regional part of the brain and is known by broad synonym as the supratentorial region, and by exact synonyms such as cerebrum and endbrain. It is a structure with developmental contributions from the neural crest and is at least part of the forebrain. Furthermore, it develops from and is an immediate transformation of some future telencephalon. The definition of telencephalon is a part of the forebrain consisting of paired olfactory bulbs and cerebral hemispheres.

The diencephalon is a regional part of the brain with various attributes and synonyms. It is a structure that contributes to development from the neural crest and is a part of the forebrain. Additionally, it develops from what is known as the future diencephalon and undergoes an immediate transformation from this future state. The definition of diencephalon is "The division of the forebrain that develops from the foremost primary cerebral vesicle." It is broadly synonymous with "DiE" and has exact synonyms including "between brain," "interbrain," "mature diencephalon," and "thalamencephalon." Furthermore, it is related to the synonyms "betweenbrain" and "diencephalon."

The hypothalamus is a regional part of the brain and constitutes at least part of the limbic system and the thalamic complex. It is defined as a specialized brain region of the ventral diencephalon arising near the end of the segmentation period; the embryonic hypothalamic region will give rise to the posterior pituitary gland as well as a number of brain nuclei, according to ZFA. Additionally, one of the most important functions of the hypothalamus, as noted by Wikipedia, is to connect the nervous system to the endocrine system through the pituitary gland (hypophysis). The hypothalamus is broadly synonymous with "Hy" and has exact synonyms including "preoptico-hypothalamic area" and "preoptico-hypothalamic region." It also has a related synonym, which is "hypothalamus" itself.

Milk is a type of bodily and mammary gland fluid secretion. It is defined as an emulsion of fat globules within a fluid that is secreted by the mammary gland during lactation. Additionally, milk has an exact synonym: mammary gland milk.

Blood plasma is a type of haemolymphatic fluid, and it is a part of blood. It is defined as the liquid component of blood, in which erythrocytes are suspended. Blood plasma has broad synonyms such as plasma and portion of plasma. Additionally, it has exact synonyms including blood plasm and portion of blood plasma.

Bile, a type of secretion of the exocrine gland, is also a type of bodily fluid. It is defined as a vital aqueous secretion of the liver that is formed by hepatocytes and subsequently modified downstream by the absorptive and secretory properties of the bile duct epithelium. Additionally, bile is related to the synonyms "fel" and "gall."

A blood vessel is a type of vessel and is derived from the mesoderm. It is part of the blood vasculature and is an epithelial tube that is open at both ends. The development of a blood vessel involves the splanchnic layer of lateral plate mesoderm and vascular cords. It is defined as a vessel through which blood circulates in the body and is broadly synonymous with a vascular element. Additionally, "region of vascular tree organ" and "vascular tree organ region" are its exact synonyms, with "vas sanguineum" being a related synonym.

    :has_broad_synonym "excreta" ;
    :has_definition "Portion of semisolid bodily waste discharged through the anus[MW,modified]." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "faeces",
        "fecal material",
        "fecal matter",
        "piece of shit",
        "portion of excrement",
        "portion of faeces",
        "portion of fecal material",
        "portion of fecal matter",
        "portion of feces",
        "portionem cacas",
        "stool" ;
    :has_narrow_synonym "cow dung",
        "cow pat",
        "dung",
        "fewmet",
        "frass",
        "guano",
        "portion of dung",
